<section xml:id="subsec-volume-of-spheres" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
    <title>Volume of Spheres</title>
    <objectives component="outcomes">
        <introduction>
            <dl>
                <li>
                    <title>Strand</title>
                    <p>
                        2.0 Measurements and Geometry
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <title>Sub-Strand</title>
                    <p>
                        2.8 Volume
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <title>Specific Learning Outcomes</title>
                    <p>
                        Calculate the volume of prisms, pyramids, cones, frustums and spheres. Explore the use of the surface area and volume of solids in real-life situations.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li component="lesson-plan">
                    <title>Grade Level</title>
                    <p>
                        10
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li component="lesson-plan">
                    <title>Estimated Duration</title>
                    <p>
                        40 minutes
                    </p>
                </li>
            </dl>
            <p component="lesson-plan">
                <p> Upon completion of this lesson, learners will be able to:
                <ol>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <alert>Know (Conceptual Understanding):</alert> Define a sphere as a perfectly round 3D object where every point on the surface is the same distance from the centre. Understand that the radius is the most important factor in determining volume and that doubling the radius increases the volume by <m>2^3 = 8</m> times.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <alert>Do (Procedural Skill):</alert> Apply the formula <m>V = \frac{4}{3}\pi r^3</m> to calculate the volume of a sphere given the radius or diameter. Solve for unknown dimensions when the volume is provided.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <alert>Apply (Application/Problem-Solving):</alert> Solve real-world problems involving sphere volumes such as sports balls, planets, raindrops, and storage tanks. Interpret how changes in the radius affect the volume.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
                </p>
            </p>
        </introduction>
    </objectives>
        <axiom component="resources">
        <!-- Link to blurb -->
        <xi:include href="../../resources-blurb-lesson.ptx" />

        <sbsgroup widths="45% 45%" margins="2% 2%">
            <sidebyside>
                <p>
                    <dataurl source="lesson_plans/measurements-and-geometry/volume/volume-of-spheres.pdf"> Lesson Plan </dataurl>
                </p>
                <p>
                    <dataurl source="lesson_plans/measurements-and-geometry/volume/step-by-step-guide_volume-of-spheres.pdf"> Step-by-Step Guide </dataurl>
                </p>
            </sidebyside>
        </sbsgroup>
    </axiom>
    <xi:include href="../../resources-materials.ptx" />

    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Phase 1: Orange Peeling Experiment</title>
        <dl>
            <li>
                <title>Suggested Time</title>
                <p>
                    15 minutes
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <title>Grouping</title>
                <p>
                    Work in small groups (3<ndash/>4 students)
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <title>Materials</title>
                <p>
                    One orange per group, knife, flat surface, calculators, worksheets for recording observations
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <title>Teacher's Role</title>
                <p>
                    Circulate among groups, ensuring students peel oranges safely. Ask probing questions: <q>What happens when you flatten the peels? How much area do they cover?</q> For struggling groups: <q>Let us peel together. What do you notice about the area?</q> For early finishers: <q>If the radius doubles, how does the volume change?</q> Guide students to articulate that the radius is the most important factor in determining the volume of a sphere.
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <title>Discussion Questions</title>
                <p>
                    <ol marker="(a)">
                        <li><p>What shape is a sphere?</p></li>
                        <li><p>What happens to the volume when the radius doubles?</p></li>
                        <li><p>Why are oranges stacked in pyramidal stacks in the market?</p></li>
                        <li><p>How does the radius affect the volume of a sphere?</p></li>
                        <li><p>Can you think of real-world examples of spheres?</p></li>
                    </ol>
                </p>
            </li>
        </dl>
        <p>
            Identify 2<ndash/>3 groups with clear findings to share with the class.
        </p>
    </axiom>

       <activity xml:id="auto_ric9u873">
        <statement>
            <p xml:id="auto_qur77g9u">
              <m>\textbf{Orange Peeling Experiment}</m>  
            </p>
            <sidebyside>
            <p xml:id="auto_zu663vm7">
                <ul xml:id="auto_r4gyx2a7">
                    <li xml:id="auto_hrhv2eqm">
                        <p xml:id="auto_8112f9l4">
                           Materials Needed:  
                        </p>
                        <p xml:id="auto_9umjbzcd">
                            ♦ An orange (or any round fruit)
                        </p>
                        <p xml:id="auto_1g6njb0s">
                            ♦ A knife
                        </p>
                        <p xml:id="auto_2mdzvyn0">
                            ♦ A flat surface
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ul>
            </p>
            <image width="50%">
            <latex-image label="borders-sphere">
                \begin{tikzpicture}
                    % Define colors
                    \definecolor{orange}{rgb}{1,0.5,0}
                    \definecolor{green}{rgb}{0,0.6,0}

                    % Function to draw an orange with a single black dot near the leaf
                    \newcommand{\draworange}[2]{
                    % Draw the main orange
                    \filldraw[fill=orange,draw=black] (#1,#2) circle(1);
                    
                    % Add a black dot near the leaf
                    \fill[black] (#1+0.3,#2+0.8) circle(0.12);

                    % Add a green leaf
                    \filldraw[fill=green,draw=black,rotate around={30:(#1,#2+1)}] 
                    (#1,#2+1) ellipse (0.5 and 0.2);
                    }

                    % Bottom layer (4 oranges)
                    \foreach \x in {0,2,4,6} {
                        \draworange{\x}{0}
                    }

                    % Second layer (3 oranges)
                    \foreach \x in {1,3,5} {
                        \draworange{\x}{1.7}
                    }

                    % Third layer (2 oranges)
                    \foreach \x in {2,4} {
                        \draworange{\x}{3.4}
                    }

                    % Top layer (1 orange)
                    \draworange{3}{5.1}

                    % Ground surface
                    \draw[thick] (-1,-1) -- (7,-1);
                    
                    % Labels
                    \node at (3,-1.5) {Pyramidal Stack of Oranges};
                \end{tikzpicture}
            </latex-image>
            </image>
                
            </sidebyside>
            <p xml:id="auto_3n5pdwfd">
                <ul xml:id="auto_dfk12zp2">
                    
                    <li xml:id="auto_5giqiwkc">
                        <p xml:id="auto_wdxxlcv7">
                            Cut the orange in half and carefully peel the skin off in small sections.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li xml:id="auto_v0kg3mvi">
                        <p xml:id="auto_gh9ftp6f">
                            Try flattening the peels and arrange them to see how they approximate a circle’s area.
                        </p>
                        <p xml:id="auto_dl4dz3v5">
                           ♦ When you peel an orange and flatten the pieces, you can see that the peels cover a large area.
                        </p>
                        <p xml:id="auto_bhrjsqug">
                            ♦ This helps visualize why increasing the radius increases the overall amount of space the fruit takes up (its volume).
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li xml:id="auto_eudjsbfi">
                        <p xml:id="auto_34b9avl4">
                           Cutting the Orange into Sections. 
                        </p>
                        <p xml:id="auto_0hs839ps">
                            ♦ If you cut an orange in half, you can see its cross-section.
                        </p>
                        <p xml:id="auto_qweuisw0">
                           ♦  If you keep slicing it into smaller spheres, their individual radii determine their volumes.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li xml:id="auto_sar8l62y">
                        <p xml:id="auto_okog3ow8">
                            Why do you think oranges or tomatoes or apples etc. are stacking in pyramidal stacks in the market?
                        </p>
                        <p xml:id="auto_mdcrn1mk">
                            ♦ Oranges in a fruit market are often packed in pyramidal stacks because spheres fit together efficiently.
                        </p>
                        <p xml:id="auto_oulf21ev">
                            ♦ The larger the radius, the more space each orange occupies, which directly affects storage and packaging.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li xml:id="auto_eyg4ouum">
                        <p xml:id="auto_m0qv30q6">
                            Key takeaways 
                        </p>

                        <p xml:id="auto_kmyjq4gz">
                            ♦ The radius is the most important factor in determining the volume of a sphere.
                        </p>
                        <p xml:id="auto_c07ekg3n">
                            ♦ If the radius doubles, the volume increases by <m>2^3 = 8</m> times!
                        </p>
                        <p xml:id="auto_4jo8s8d7">
                            ♦ This explains why a slightly bigger orange holds significantly more juice compared to a smaller one.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ul>
            </p>    
        </statement>
       </activity>
       <p xml:id="auto_oeirvehu">
            <m>\textbf{Key Takeaway}</m>
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_xlajrfbr">

        A sphere is a perfectly round object.
       </p>

    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Phase 2: Formalizing the Sphere Volume Formula</title>
        <dl>
            <li>
                <title>Suggested Time</title>
                <p>
                    10 minutes
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <title>Grouping</title>
                <p>
                    Whole class
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <title>Scaffolding Strategies to Address Misconceptions</title>
                <p>
                    <ul>
                        <li><p><alert>Misconception:</alert> A sphere is the same as a circle. <alert>Clarification:</alert> A circle is two-dimensional (flat), while a sphere is three-dimensional (round).</p></li>
                        <li><p><alert>Misconception:</alert> The volume formula is <m>\pi r^3</m>. <alert>Clarification:</alert> You must multiply by <m>\frac{4}{3}</m>. The formula is <m>\frac{4}{3}\pi r^3</m>.</p></li>
                        <li><p><alert>Misconception:</alert> If the radius doubles, the volume doubles. <alert>Clarification:</alert> If the radius doubles, the volume increases by <m>8</m> times (<m>2^3 = 8</m>).</p></li>
                        <li><p><alert>Misconception:</alert> I can use the diameter instead of the radius. <alert>Clarification:</alert> The formula uses the radius. If you have the diameter, divide by 2 to get the radius.</p></li>
                    </ul>
                </p>
            </li>
        </dl>
    </axiom>

    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Phase 3: Practice and Application</title>
        <dl>
            <li>
                <title>Suggested Time</title>
                <p>
                    10 minutes
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <title>Grouping</title>
                <p>
                    Individual, then pairs for checking
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <title>Teacher's Role</title>
                <p>
                    Walk through the first worked example on the board, then allow students to attempt the second example independently. Circulate to check working and provide support where needed.
                </p>
            </li>
        </dl>
    </axiom>

       <example xml:id="auto_93iy8eqr">
       <statement>
        <p xml:id="auto_tf6quisv">
             A sphere has a radius of 6 cm. Find its volume.
        </p>  
        <p xml:id="auto_9vfhqxsv">
          <md>
            <mrow> \text{V} =\amp \frac{4}{3} \times \pi r^3</mrow>
            <mrow>  = \amp 3.142 \times \frac{4}{3} \times (6)^3</mrow>
            <mrow> = \amp \frac {864}{3} \times 3.142 </mrow>
            <mrow> = \amp 904.9 \, \text{cm}^3</mrow>
          </md>  
        </p>
       </statement>
        
       </example>
       <example xml:id="auto_g6o6xyo5">
        <statement>
            <p xml:id="auto_u6ooq3ga">
                A football has a radius of 9 cm. What is the volume of the ball?
            </p>

        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p xml:id="auto_u2nn2jfi">
                <md>
                    <mrow> \text{V} =\amp \frac{4}{3} \times \pi r^3</mrow>
                    <mrow>  = \amp 3.142 \times \pi\frac{4}{3} \times (9 \,\text{cm})^3</mrow>
                    <mrow> = \amp 3054.02\, \text{cm}^3</mrow>
                </md>  
            </p>
        </solution>
       </example>
       <example xml:id="auto_ix2tk448">
        <statement>
            <p xml:id="auto_alvrw1jt">
                A planet has a radius of 1000 km. What's it's volume?
            </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p xml:id="auto_i2i8zpnc">
                <md>
                    <mrow> \text{V} =\amp \frac{4}{3} \times r^3</mrow>
                    <mrow>  = \amp 3.142 \times\frac{4}{3} \times (1000)^3</mrow>
                    <mrow> = \amp 4,189,333,333 4.19= \ 10^9\, \text{km}^3</mrow>
                </md>  
                
            </p>
        </solution>
       </example>
    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Phase 4: Assessment</title>
        <dl>
            <li>
                <title>Suggested Time</title>
                <p>
                    5 minutes
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <title>Grouping</title>
                <p>
                    Individual
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <title>Exit Ticket</title>
                <p>
                    Students complete questions 1<ndash/>3 individually.
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <title>Answer Key (Teacher Reference)</title>
                <p>
                    <ol marker="1.">
                        <li><p><m>V = \frac{4}{3}\pi(7)^3 = 1436.76\,\text{cm}^3</m></p></li>
                        <li><p>Hemisphere: radius <m>= 6</m> cm. <m>V = \frac{2}{3}\pi(6)^3 = 452.39\,\text{cm}^3</m></p></li>
                        <li><p>If radius doubles, volume increases by <m>8</m> times. New volume <m>= 500 \times 8 = 4000\,\text{cm}^3</m>.</p></li>
                    </ol>
                </p>
            </li>
        </dl>
    </axiom>

       <p xml:id="auto_rr71pv2d">
        <m>\textbf{Exercise}</m>
       </p>
       <sidebyside>
        <p xml:id="auto_8diow2g5">
        1. A solid sphere has a radius of 7 cm. Find its volume.
       </p>
       <image width="45%">
            <shortdescription> Sphere </shortdescription>
            <latex-image label="sphere-example-t">
                \begin{tikzpicture}
                    % Draw the main circle
                    \draw [thick,blue!70](0,0) circle (2);
                    
                    % Draw the dashed ellipse inside the circle
                    \draw[dashed,red!50] (-2,0) arc (180:360:2 and 0.5);
                    \draw[dashed,red!50] (2,0) arc (0:180:2 and 0.5);
                    
                    
                    % Draw and label the center point
                    \fill (0,0) circle (0.05);
                    \node[above right] at (0.5,0) {\small $r =7 cm$};
                    
                    % Draw the radius line
                    \draw[dashed] (0,0) -- (2,0);
                \end{tikzpicture}
            </latex-image>
        </image>
       </sidebyside>
    
       <p xml:id="auto_a1pexx05">
        2. A bowl is in the shape of a hemisphere with a diameter of 12 cm.
       Find the volume of the bowl.
       </p>
      <sidebyside>
         <p xml:id="auto_7dq03iq2">
        3. A sphere has a volume of 500 cm³. If the radius is doubled, what will be the new volume?
       </p><image width="45%">
            <shortdescription> Sphere </shortdescription>
            <latex-image label="sphere-example-r">
                \begin{tikzpicture}
                    % Draw the main circle
                    \draw [thick,magenta!70](0,0) circle (2);
                    
                    % Draw the dashed ellipse inside the circle
                    \draw[dashed,cyan] (-2,0) arc (180:360:2 and 0.5);
                    \draw[dashed,cyan] (2,0) arc (0:180:2 and 0.5);
                    
                    
                    % Draw and label the center point
                    \fill (0,0) circle (0.05);
                    \node[above right] at (-1,-0.8) {\small $V = 500cm^3$};
                    
                    % Draw the radius line
                    \draw[dashed] (0,0) -- (2,0);
                \end{tikzpicture}
            </latex-image>
        </image>
      </sidebyside>
       <p xml:id="auto_eotoyijs">
        4. A raindrop is modeled as a sphere with a radius of 0.2 cm. If a storm produces 1,000,000 raindrops,
        what is the total volume of water in liters?
       </p>
       
        <sidebyside>
        <image width="45%">
           <latex-image label="sphere-purple">
            \begin{tikzpicture}
                % Draw the sphere
                \shade[ball color=purple!70] (0,0) circle (2cm);
                
                % Draw equator line
                \draw[dashed] (-2,0) arc (180:360:2cm and 0.5cm);
                \draw (-2,0) arc (180:0:2cm and 0.5cm);
                
                % Draw vertical meridian
                \draw[dashed] (0,-2) arc (-90:90:0.5cm and 2cm);
                \draw (0,2) arc (90:270:0.5cm and 2cm);
                
                % Draw radius
                \draw[thick, yellow] (0,0) -- (2,0) node[midway, above] {$r = 12$ cm};
                
                % Label sphere
                \node at (0,-2.5) {Sphere with radius \( r = 12cm \)};
            \end{tikzpicture}
           </latex-image>
           </image>
        <p xml:id="auto_dt1xk8tg">
           5  A basketball has a radius of 12 cm, while a tennis ball has a radius of 4 cm.
        How many tennis balls can fit inside the basketball, assuming no empty space?
       </p> 
        </sidebyside>
       
       
          


