            </exercise>

    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Differentiation Strategies</title>
        <p>
            <alert>For Struggling Learners:</alert>
            <ul>
                <li><p>Provide pre-cut oranges with labeled radii.</p></li>
                <li><p>Use spheres with simple dimensions for initial practice.</p></li>
                <li><p>Pair struggling students with confident problem solvers.</p></li>
                <li><p>Provide step-by-step calculation templates.</p></li>
                <li><p>Allow use of calculators for all calculations.</p></li>
                <li><p>Break down the formula into steps: calculate <m>r^3</m>, multiply by <m>\pi</m>, multiply by 4, divide by 3.</p></li>
            </ul>
        </p>
        <p>
            <alert>For On-Level Learners:</alert>
            <ul>
                <li><p>Encourage students to verify their formula with orange peeling.</p></li>
                <li><p>Ask students to explain the relationship between radius and volume.</p></li>
                <li><p>Provide mixed practice with different dimensions.</p></li>
                <li><p>Challenge students to find the volume when only the diameter is given.</p></li>
            </ul>
        </p>
        <p>
            <alert>For Advanced Learners:</alert>
            <ul>
                <li><p>Explore real-world applications: sports balls, planets, bubbles, water tanks.</p></li>
                <li><p>Investigate the cubic relationship between radius and volume.</p></li>
                <li><p>Apply the concept to hemispheres (half-spheres).</p></li>
                <li><p>Solve optimisation problems: Given a fixed volume, what radius minimises the surface area?</p></li>
            </ul>
        </p>
        <p>
            <alert>Extension Activity <mdash/> Raindrop Volume Investigation:</alert> In groups, model a raindrop as a sphere with radius 0.2 cm. Calculate the volume of one raindrop, then multiply by 1,000,000 to find total volume in cm<m>^3</m>. Convert to litres (<m>1\,\text{L} = 1000\,\text{cm}^3</m>). Compare different raindrop sizes: 0.3 cm and 0.4 cm radius.
        </p>
    </axiom>

    <xi:include href="../../resources-assessment.ptx" />
